ce:section.ce:para:
The validity of the computational model employed in this research was established by comparing its outcomes with the well-regarded Taylor two-dimensional film boiling model for a pure fluid, which is supported by well-documented experimental findings. Although the primary focus of this investigation centers on the dynamics of vertical film boiling, the utilization of Taylor’s model – predominantly recognized for its application in horizontal film boiling scenarios – served as a rigorous validation framework. This choice was motivated by the model’s recognized precision, the availability of experimental correlations for comparative analysis, and its relevance to simulating conditions similar to those encountered in vertical film boiling phenomena explored in this study. The essential thermophysical parameters used for this purpose are detailed in Table 3. For the sake of validation, simulations were performed under the assumption of no nanoparticles present (
φ = 0
), with the boundary and initial conditions, alongside the detailed geometry of the study domain, illustrated in Fig. 3. Further information regarding the benchmark configuration and its associated parameters is extensively covered in prior studies [86–88].
